Today we’re coaching two amazing moms - both already in one of my courses - and who want a little more support working through some issues to give them peace of mind and help get them to that next step. 

Mom #1 - 8.5 month old not drinking from a straw despite lots of practice 

Mom #2 - 21 month old getting increasingly picky and hard to deal with at mealtimes - mom can’t figure out why. 

Want to get monthly coaching from me too? I’m launching a membership in June for all my course clients to give you:
- live coaching calls with me
- monthly baby and toddler frequently recipes
- New video content in our video library answering q&a’s, showing you demos and more 
- Guides and resources to help you navigate feeding and nutrition in a more practical way 
- Guest speakers and guest activities. 

If you are interested and want to get in on a founding members price, click the link in my profile to get on the waitlist!

node.text:
Pressure at mealtimes is well intention behaviour from us parents that backfires when it comes to getting kids to eat better and love mealtimes. This happens for a very specific reason that has to do with the emotional state of the child and the experience in a pressured environment. 

This video walks you through what it would feel like for YOU to be pressured at the table, with a very convincing story I’m sure will help you understand exactly what your child is feeling. 

I’d love for you to tell me your thoughts and share your experience with being pressured to eat, and how that affected you either as a child, or even now into adulthood. 

Challenge yourself to stay silent about food for the next couple weeks and check back with me. Your ticket to having your picky eater learning to love a variety of foods starts HERE.

node.title: Pressure at mealtimes (what it feels like for your toddler)

What if I was to tell you that everything you thought you knew about limiting baby’s salt intake was false? 😳😲🙀

I’ve even touted many times the guideline that “we should limit baby’s salt intake to 400 mg/day, with only 200 mg coming from food and 200 mg from breastmilk”. 🙋🏻‍♀️

Well - after having the pleasure of speaking with @lilynicholsrdn who basically debunked everything we thought we knew around why this was the case - I’m giving you permission to let go of the stress and let your baby share in your family’s home cooked meals without worrying about separating food with no salt for baby. I also don’t want you to stress about the sodium in certain fish, or the sodium in certain cheese that’s not offered everyday.

✳️There’s NO EVIDENCE that babies need this EXTREME low salt diet that we all think they do.✳️

Want to know more? Head to the link in my profile to read my blog on this topic or listen to the podcast episode around this. 🔗🔗🔗

What are your thoughts? Let me know in the comments below!!👇👇

node.title: The real truth about salt limits for babies

Phase 3 of the Texture Timeline™ is the FINAL phase! This phase focuses on expanding through the full range of textures out there - everything from spongy textures to stringy and chewy to grainy, and more!

Today we’re doing stringy texture! 

At this stage, no specific order is required - this is all about experimentation and learning! This phase is really great for giving your baby that exposure to a wide variety of the foods we as parents would eat. It also gets them learning early, while taking advantage of this critical period where they willingly accept and want to learn how to eat new food. They’ve experienced all the basics at this point, and from here on out it’s a lot of practice!

node.text:
Phase 3 of the Texture Timeline™ is the FINAL phase! This phase focuses on expanding through the full range of textures out there - everything from spongy textures to stringy and chewy to grainy, and more!

Today we’re doing spongy texture! 

At this stage, no specific order is required - this is all about experimentation and learning! This phase is really great for giving your baby that exposure to a wide variety of the foods we as parents would eat. It also gets them learning early, while taking advantage of this critical period where they willingly accept and want to learn how to eat new food. They’ve experienced all the basics at this point, and from here on out it’s a lot of practice!

Want to learn more about feeding your baby form 6-12 months in a way to prevent picky eating? node.text:
What is Phase 2 all about?
Phase 2 is all about offering larger lumps or minced textures! Foods that fall into this phase are still soft and squishable, but pose more of a challenge for babies because they have to work harder to manipulate this texture in their mouth. These foods can be mashed and then swallowed, or break apart easily in their mouth without the need for heavy chewing - but still have a bit more of a bite! The food will be lumpier, more irregular in shape, and may contain mixed soft textures. Most babies can tolerate this stage fairly early after starting solids, or even as the first texture offered!

Watch the live and let’s help you advance your baby on in textures to prevent picky eating and be sure to check out my Baby Led Feeding online course for all you need to know about feeding your baby from 6-12 months!

node.text:
We’re working on Phase 1 on my Texture Timeline!

This is technically the phase that the majority of babies can handle right from the start, and that usually isn't too scary for most parents. It’s those thick, creamy, and mashed textures, as well as very soft solids! 
This phase allows your baby to feel the texture in their mouth and provides more sensory input, so that they learn to manipulate it on their tongue, and in their mouth, without any chewing required! We’re gently challenging their oral motor skills!

Typically, this phase can last anywhere from 1-14 days.

So many of us start solids feeling SO unsure about things and sometimes even afraid of make moves into the world of texture or finger foods because of lack of confidence. 

In this video, I talk about how I can help you build your confidence through this starting solids journey!

Tip #1: Focus on where you are - not where everyone else is
Tip #2 - Set mini-goals
Tip #2 - Take action EVERY day!

Listen in for the full details. YOU CAN DO THIS!

Oh! And if you’re ready to join the 5 day Texture Timeline ™ challenge to help your baby advance in textures and skills in a step-by-step manner, sign up here
https://courses.mylittleeater.com/texturetimelinechallenge or by clicking the link in my profile!

node.text:
A tip that will go a long way for you AND your kiddo!

Making lunches look fun and interesting to eat doesn’t have to take much extra time. Add a pop of colour and create a bigger buffet of options by simply adding some muffin tin liners to your bugger compartments! It also makes it SO much easier on you to figure out how you can add variety to your child’s lunch and avoid having food touch each other without having a specific divider for every type of food!

You can find these fun silicone muffin liners in my Amazon shop! Link in profile 🔗

node.text:
Young kids will not instinctively ask for help opening lunch containers if they’re struggling. They may struggle for a really long time on their own (which means they barely have time to eat) or likely just give up and not eat anything.

Practice opening all lunchboxes, containers, lids etc. With your child BEFORE sending them off to school! Do it the week leading up to school and role play what to do if they’re struggling and how to ask for help!

node.text:
Did you know that there's really no need for baby oat cereal (or any infant cereal) at all? ⠀⁠⠀
⠀⁠⠀
Can it be used? Sure! ⠀⁠⠀
⠀⁠⠀
But there's no harm of offering regular "adult" oatmeal to babies starting around 6 months of age either! The reason for offering infant versions of any cereals (rice, oat, mixed grain etc.) is because it's been fortified with iron, which is an important nutrient for babies. But it has nothing to do with textures or anything harmful in regular oatmeal at all. And if your baby is being offered 2 sources of heme iron foods per day, there's no need to have to rely on infant cereals for iron at all (especially if you're formula feeding). ⠀⁠⠀
⠀⁠⠀
Here are my tips for preparing oatmeal for babies:⠀⁠⠀
⠀⁠⠀
▶️ You can use any type really...rolled, steel cut, old fashioned etc. They're all fine and safe for baby! Some parents grind up the oatmeal into more of a powdered texture before cooking it. There's really no need to do this, unless you're cautiously easing into the first stage of the Texture Timeline™ and will be swiftly moving them up from that texture once you see they can safely swallow. (Learn more about the Texture Timeline™ by checking out my highlighted stories on this topic).⠀⁠⠀
⠀⁠⠀
▶️ Preparing oatmeal with milk for babies gives them more calories, fat and nutrients so I recommend using breastmilk or formula to prepare it for those reasons. With breastmilk, you can prepare the oatmeal over the stove with water and add the breastmilk/formula in after it's been cooked to avoid heating it too much!⁠⠀
⠀⁠⠀
▶️ Go ahead and get creative with add ins! Avoid all forms of added sugar (even natural sugars like maple syrup), but go ahead and try different mashed/diced fruit in there. You can even mix in thin amounts of a nut butter if you want! I love add different baby-safe seeds like hemp seeds, flax seeds and/or chia cheese for lots of extra nutrition!⠀⁠⠀
⠀⁠⠀
Have you given your baby "adult" oatmeal before? At what age did you start?

PS - I have a free guide on how much food your baby should be eating - see link in my profile!

node.text:
What do YOU say when your toddler says "I don't like this"❓Tell me below! 👇⁠⠀
⁠⠀
Listen, we all love a good script to get our toddlers to do xyz (that of course you can modify as you see fit). And in episode 70 of The My Little Eater Podcast, I run through some examples of what you can say to your toddler to create a no pressure environment that gets them to EAT.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
Now, they may not try a new food the very FIRST time it’s offered to them, but with exposure and the phrases I’m sharing, they'll learn a growth mindset around food and be more open to trying new foods in the future. Your toddler’s feelings will be considered while AT THE SAME TIME they're getting to explore food at their own pace.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
Here are some examples when they say "I don't like that!!" ⁠⠀
⁠⠀
You say:⁠⠀
⁠⠀
🥦"That's ok! You don't have to eat it!"⁠⠀
🥦"Remember how our taste buds change every month? You can test out to see if yours have changed or if they're still the same!"⁠⠀
🥦"You don't like it YET. That's ok! You may like it soon".⁠⠀
⁠⠀
There's more to it of course. But you'll have to tune into the episode to find out more :) ⁠⠀
⁠⠀

node.text:
Trouble teaching your little one to drink from a straw cup? Here’s a hack!

Use an inexpensive Take and Toss cup for teaching this skill - as early as 9 months of age! Fill it with some water (1/2 cup is more than enough), have your child put the straw in their mouth and give it a GENTLE squeeze (it comes out fast!). Your child will begin to associate the straw as a place water comes out.

After a few times, do it again but this time, don’t squeeze until they’ve wrapped their lips around it!  Try again and then this time, wait for them to suck!

Not all kids need this help, but if you’ve tried for a few months and they’re still having trouble, this could be the solution for you!

Found this helpful? Share with a friend! ❤️❤️

node.text:
So seriously, how can you get your toddler to Just. Drink. More. Water?! ⠀⠀
⠀⠀
🔵 Pick a fun water bottle!⠀⠀
⠀⠀
Better yet, let them pick (if they’re able to of course)! This can be fun for them and gives them a little independence too. Let’s give a big high five to all those water bottle companies that make water bottles with Paw Patrol and Peppa Pig – they knew what you needed before you did 😉⠀⠀
⠀⠀
🔵 Prompt your toddler to drink from a water bottle every half hour⠀⠀
⠀⠀
Put that fun water bottle to good use and keep it full with cool, fresh water all day long. If your toddler has access to it, and knows milk or juice is off the table between meals and snacks, they’ll be more likely to quench their thirst with water instead.Prompt them often by setting a timer. Every time it goes off, say “It’s time for a water break!”. Make it fun and even turn it into a game! Who can be the first to race to find their water bottle and take a sip? Maybe declare how hard you’ve worked and brag about how much you deserve this sip of water. ⠀
⠀⠀
🔵 Add in novelty with ice cubes and straws!⠀⠀
⠀⠀
Add ice cubes or a crazy straw to their water for something new and different! Bring more novelty into it by making them their own special ice cubes using different ice cube molds. You can find suggestions for ice cube molds and straw in my Amazon shops (link in profile)⠀⠀
⠀⠀
🔵 The rubber band trick⠀⠀
⠀⠀
Put a rubber band on their water bottle to signify where you’d like them to drink to. Dare them, challenge them...even use a little reverse psychology! "Can you drink to the rubber band? Bet you can't!"⠀
⠀⠀
🔵 Add fresh fruit⠀⠀
⠀⠀
Add frozen/fresh fruit/veggies. Entice them without the added sugar that juice would have. Some good choices include berries, oranges, lemons, or cucumbers.⠀
⠀⠀
🔵 Be a role model⠀⠀
⠀⠀
Use exaggerated sounds that make it sound so good and refreshing that they’ll really want to try! Make big “AHHH” sounds after you⠀
⠀

With summer weather upon us, our mommy-senses go way up for making sure our toddlers get enough hydration in all this heat. That's why I've written a blog post all about how to achieve proper hydration and get your toddler to drink more water!! Head to the link in my profile to read all about it 👆⠀⁠
⠀⁠
1-3 year olds need 3.5-5 cups (8 oz = cup) of fluid/day which all depends on their age, size, physical activity level, and even gender. ⠀⁠
⠀⁠
I want you to know that fluid doesn't necessarily mean just water...it can be milk, juice or fluid from foods, specifically those that are more hydrating. We typically want to avoid or minimally serve juice, so for the purposes of the example below, I'm not going to count juice as a way to meet hydration needs. ⠀⁠
⠀⁠
Here's what this COULD look like (remember, your child's diet may look different, that that's totally fine!). ⠀⁠
⠀⁠
- 2 x 8 oz cups of milk/day⠀⁠
- 2 x 8 oz cups of water/day⠀⁠
- 1 cup of fluid coming from generally eating hydrating foods (check out the blog post for ideas on hydrating foods).⠀⁠
⠀⁠
You don't have to be a stickler about counting this every single day, but be mindful of the fact that you are offering more hydrating foods in the summer months and days where the heat is strong, and always have water on hand between meals and snacks for them to sip on. Every bit counts! Watch for signs of dehydration and adjust accordingly :)⠀⁠
⠀⁠
Tomorrow, I'll talk about some of my fav tips to help your toddler drink more water. ⠀⁠
